# xlang Library API Rules

Libraries under `libs/` are **not** syscall bridges. They must expose **instance/context APIs**.

## Forbidden in `libs/`

- Mutable module-level state used as implicit context (`req: Request`, `listen: ServerInfo`, `dispatch_on`, …)
- Free functions that take the instance as first arg when a method exists (`Foo(ctx, …)` call style from outside)
- Handle-style APIs for library types (`LockAcquire(l, 0)`, `DispatchRequest(r, …)` as module fn)

## Allowed module-level in `libs/`

- `const` / static literals only (if the language supports them)
- Type/struct definitions
- Private helpers (`fn register_route(...)`)

## Required patterns

```xlang
// Factory returns instance
local r = http.NewRouter()

// Methods on instance
r.Get("/ping", handle_ping)
r.DispatchRequest("GET", "/ping")
r.ListenAndServe("127.0.0.1", 8080, on_listen)

// Per-request/per-callback context passed explicitly to handlers
fn handle_ping(req: Request) {
    req.RespondText(200, "pong")
}

fn on_listen(info: ServerInfo) {
    print("%s://%s:%d", info.Protocol(), info.Hostname(), info.Port())
}
```

## Concurrency

Never store per-request state in module globals — parallel handlers/spawn will race. Create context on the stack/heap inside `DispatchRequest` (or equivalent) and pass it via `invoke1(handler, ctx)`.

## Syscalls vs libraries

- **`declare syscall`** — OS bridge only; handle/int64 fds are OK here and in `runtime/`
- **`libs/`** — domain API; return structs, use methods, pass context into callbacks
